### Define a Root Layout in Next.js App Router

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/03-file-conventions/layout.mdx

This code defines a basic root layout component for a Next.js application using the App Router. The root layout is the top-most layout and must include <html> and <body> tags. It receives `children` as a prop, which represents the content of nested layouts or pages. This layout serves as the base structure for all pages within the application.

```tsx
export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <html>
      <body>{children}</body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

```jsx
export default function RootLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <html>
      <body>{children}</body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

--------------------------------

### Create Root Layout Component - Next.js App Directory

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/migrating/app-router-migration.mdx

Define a root layout component that wraps all routes in the app directory. The layout must accept a children prop and define html and body tags. Supports both TypeScript (.tsx) and JavaScript (.jsx) file extensions.

```typescript
export default function RootLayout({
  // Layouts must accept a children prop.
  // This will be populated with nested layouts or pages
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>{children}</body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

```javascript
export default function RootLayout({
  // Layouts must accept a children prop.
  // This will be populated with nested layouts or pages
  children,
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>{children}</body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

--------------------------------

### Create a Root Layout Component

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/01-getting-started/03-layouts-and-pages.mdx

A layout is a shared UI component that wraps pages and nested layouts. The root layout is mandatory, must be defined at the root of the app directory, and must include html and body tags.

```tsx
export default function DashboardLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>
        {/* Layout UI */}
        {/* Place children where you want to render a page or nested layout */}
        <main>{children}</main>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

```jsx
export default function DashboardLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>
        {/* Layout UI */}
        {/* Place children where you want to render a page or nested layout */}
        <main>{children}</main>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

### Creating a Root Layout > Root Layout Requirements

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/migrating/app-router-migration.mdx

The `app` directory must include a root layout file (`app/layout.tsx`). This root layout applies to all routes inside the `app` directory and replaces the `pages/_app.tsx` and `pages/_document.tsx` files from the pages directory. The root layout must define `<html>` and `<body>` tags since Next.js does not automatically create them. Layout files can use `.js`, `.jsx`, or `.tsx` extensions.

--------------------------------

### Root Layout

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/03-file-conventions/layout.mdx

The `app` directory **must** include a **root layout**, which is the top-most layout in the root `app` directory. Typically, the root layout is `app/layout.js`. The root layout **must** define `<html>` and `<body>` tags. You should **not** manually add `<head>` tags such as `<title>` and `<meta>` to root layouts. Instead, you should use the [Metadata API](/docs/app/getting-started/metadata-and-og-images) which automatically handles advanced requirements such as streaming and de-duplicating `<head>` elements.

